chatgpt on services:
--------------------
I‚Äôll walk you through what works on WCOSS2, what usually doesn‚Äôt, and a realistic deployment pattern people at NOAA actually use.

1. Reality check: what you probably do not have on WCOSS2
On WCOSS2, assume:

‚ùå Docker / Podman
‚ùå systemd access
‚ùå root privileges
‚ùå long-running internet-facing daemons
‚ùå Redis / RabbitMQ

Maybe:

FastAPI / uvicorn ‚ùì

Python 3 via modules ‚úî

SQLite ‚úî

Slurm / PBS / LSF ‚úî (WCOSS2 = Slurm)

So forget ‚Äúweb service listening on a port‚Äù as your primary mechanism.

2. The WCOSS2-native pattern (this is the key insight)
On WCOSS2, the service is not a daemon.

Instead, it is:

A command-line service + scheduler integration

Think:

request  ‚Üí  writes DB entry  ‚Üí  submits Slurm job  ‚Üí  job runs converter
This is still a service ‚Äî just job-driven, not socket-driven.

3. What ‚Äúdeployment‚Äù means on WCOSS2
Deployment =

Put code in $HOME or /lfs/h2/...

Load modules

Create a CLI entry point

Submit jobs with sbatch

Use SQLite for coordination

That‚Äôs it.

No always-on process.

4. Minimal WCOSS2-compatible service design
Components
ioda_service/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ ioda_service.py      # CLI entry point (the "service")
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ runner.py            # runs one obs_space_cycle
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ db.sqlite
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ submit_cycle.sh      # Slurm submission script
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ logs/
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ modules.sh
5. The ‚Äúservice‚Äù is a CLI
ioda_service.py
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import argparse
import sqlite3
import subprocess

def submit_cycle(cycle):
    db = sqlite3.connect("db.sqlite")
    rows = db.execute(
        "SELECT id FROM obs_space_cycle WHERE cycle_time=?",
        (cycle,)
    ).fetchall()

    for (osc_id,) in rows:
        subprocess.run(
            ["sbatch", "submit_cycle.sh", str(osc_id)],
            check=True
        )

if __name__ == "__main__":
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()
    parser.add_argument("--cycle", required=True)
    args = parser.parse_args()

    submit_cycle(args.cycle)
Run it like:

./ioda_service.py --cycle 2026012912
That is your service request.

6. Slurm job script (this is your worker)
submit_cycle.sh
#!/bin/bash
#SBATCH --job-name=ioda_conv
#SBATCH --time=00:10:00
#SBATCH --nodes=1
#SBATCH --ntasks=1
#SBATCH --partition=service
#SBATCH --output=logs/%j.out
#SBATCH --error=logs/%j.err

source modules.sh
python3 runner.py "$1"
7. The runner (stateless, pure)
runner.py
import sys
import sqlite3
import subprocess

osc_id = int(sys.argv[1])

db = sqlite3.connect("db.sqlite")

row = db.execute(
    """SELECT input_path, output_path, parameters_json, converter
       FROM obs_space_cycle WHERE id=?""",
    (osc_id,)
).fetchone()

input_path, output_path, params, converter = row

cmd = [
    converter,
    "--input", input_path,
    "--output", output_path
]

subprocess.run(cmd, check=True)
That‚Äôs it. No service running forever. Slurm is your scheduler, retry system, and monitor.

8. Modules instead of pip installs
On WCOSS2 you should expect:

module avail python
module load python/3.9.12
Create modules.sh:

module purge
module load python/3.9.12
If FastAPI isn‚Äôt available ‚Äî no problem ‚Äî you don‚Äôt need it.

9. SQLite is fine on WCOSS2 (with rules)
SQLite works well if:

‚úî Writes are infrequent
‚úî One writer at a time
‚úî DB is on a shared filesystem (Lustre is OK)

Best practice:

One Slurm job = one obs_space_cycle

Short transactions

Commit fast

10. How this maps perfectly to your use case
Concept	WCOSS2 reality
Service	CLI + DB
Request	./ioda_service.py --cycle X
Workers	Slurm jobs
Async	Scheduler
Retry	Re-submit job
Status	DB column
Logs	Slurm stdout/err
This is idiomatic NOAA HPC design.

11. If you really want HTTP later
You can:

Run FastAPI on a login node

Bind to localhost

Use SSH port forwarding

But I would strongly advise:
‚û° start CLI + Slurm first
‚û° add HTTP only if a real user needs it

12. Sanity check: you‚Äôre not behind
What you‚Äôre proposing:

DB-driven

Cycle-based

Stateless workers

Scheduler-backed execution

‚Ä¶is exactly how big NOAA systems are built.

